<F P=102>   EA1106202394 Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in Arabic 1500 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1106202394 </F>
<F P=104>  Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in Arabic 1500 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brother 'Ali Salim al-Bid, chairman of the 
Presidential Council, met this morning brothers Haydar Abu-Bakr 
al-'Attas, the chairman of the Council of Ministers; 'Abdallah 
'Abd-al-Majid al- Asnaj, deputy premier and foreign minister; 
Muhsin Abu-Bakr Bin Farid, deputy premier and minister of 
planning and development; and Salih Ubayd Ahmad, minister of 
transport and communications. 
  The prime minister briefed his brother the chairman of the 
Presidential Council on the outcome of the tours made by him and 
his deputies to Saudi Arabia, Egypt, the United Arab Emirates 
[UAE] and Kuwait as well as on his meetings with the leaders of 
those countries and their briefings on the latest developments 
in the Yemeni crisis and the war imposed on our Yemeni people by 
the gang of the bloody al-Ahmar family. 
  Brother 'Ali Salim al-Bid welcomed the patriotic personality 
of al-Ustadh 'Abdallah 'Abd-al-Majid al-Asnaj who returned to 
the homeland to participate with his brothers in building the 
Democratic Republic of Yemen, a new modern state, a state of law 
and order. The brother chairman of the Presidential Council 
expressed his satisfaction about the outcome of the tours made 
and praised the stand of those countries and their leaders on 
the side of the cause of our Yemeni people as well as their 
efforts at the Arab and international levels to stop this 
destructive war which causes concern for the security and 
stability of Yemen and the region. Brother 'Ali Salim al-Bid 
reiterated the unilateral and strict commitment of the 
Democratic Republic of Yemen to the decision of the UN Security 
Council Resolution No. 924 on the cease-fire. 
  He stressed that all efforts must be concerted to implement 
the Security Council resolution and to compel the Sanaa military 
regime, which is challenging international legitimacy and is 
violating the council's resolution, to abide by the cease-fire 
resolution, stop the war and resort to peaceful dialogue to 
tackle the political situation. 

</TEXT>

