<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aden Accuses Jordan of Supporting Northern Cause </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aden Accuses Jordan of Supporting Northern Cause </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1006121194 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 10 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1006121194 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Lutfi Shatarah] </F>
  [Text] London -- 'Abdallah al-Asnaj, foreign minister of 
the Democratic Republic of Yemen [DRY], has accused Jordan of 
involvement in the ongoing fighting in Yemen alongside the 
forces loyal to the Sanaa leadership. He told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT 
over the telephone from Abu Dhabi that 30 Jordanian military air 
engineers are equipping Northern U.S.-made F-5 fighter aircraft 
with spare parts -- "which has helped to restore their 
combat-readiness, thus enabling them to participate in recent 
battles." 
  Al-Asnaj said that "the DRY authorities are investigating 
this involvement with the Jordanian quarters concerned and with 
a number of Arab states, on the grounds that this involvement is 
one of the factors contributing to escalating the war." 
  It is worth mentioning that a high-ranking Western 
diplomatic 
source, who asked to remain anonymous, told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT 
that "some reports say that Yemen is obtaining arms from 
Russia." The sources added that "Jordan may be the channel 
through which the arms are imported for Sanaa." 
  Al-Asnaj pointed out that Northern aircraft, which have 
resumed their attacks recently, "are bombing civilian targets in 
the Aden suburbs." He stressed that "the DRY will cooperate 
with any measures taken by the Security Council to secure a 
cease-fire, and may apply to the Council again if [UN secretary 
general's envoy Lakhdar] Brahimi's mission fails." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

