<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier al-'Attas on Priority Task of Halting War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier al-'Attas on Priority Task of Halting War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1006121994 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 10 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM1006121994 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Taj-al-Din 'Abd-al-Haqq] </F>
  [Text] Abu Dhabi -- Engineer Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas, 
prime minister of the Democratic Republic of Yemen [DRY], has 
said that Aden does not object to the dispatch to Yemen of an 
Arab deterrent force to observe the cease-fire and disengage the 
forces. 
  He said this in a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Abu 
Dhabi 
yesterday. Al-'Attas said that the DRY's priority now is "a 
cease-fire and then to discuss the procedures for disengaging 
the forces and deploying observers." 
  He added that the DRY urges the Gulf Cooperation Council 
[GCC] states and Egypt, to which the credit for the UN Security 
Council resolution goes, to continue their role in the Security 
Council so that the council may continue to implement its 
resolution and take the necessary measures for that in 
accordance with the stipulations of the UN Charter. 
  Al-'Attas said that "Recognition of the DRY is not our 
priority, because recognition has become a reality since war 
broke out. The pressing question now is to halt the war." He 
pointed out that northern forces have recently -- having failed 
to achieve the aims it had set for themselves -- resorted to 
hitting residential areas and civilian and economic 
installations. Al-'Attas said that Aden's contacts with the GCC 
states have borne fruit over the past two days, as the United 
States has issued a new statement expressing utmost concern over 
the continuation of the fighting and openly expressing its 
position calling for an immediate halt to the war. 
  He stressed that the continuation of the war will result in 
numerous complications, and that "the northerners' insistence on 
continuing it reflects despair and loss of control." 
  On the Arab League's exclusion from the diplomatic efforts 
Aden is making, al-'Attas said that "the DRY has from the outset 
referred to the Arab League, and contacts are continuing with 
it, as a meeting has been held with the Arab League secretary 
general." 
  He pointed out that the league supports the UN Security 
Council resolution, but the conditions the Arab League is 
experiencing are not helping it to take a decision. He said 
that "the DRY welcomes any role by the league in the framework 
of the UN Security Council resolution." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

