<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visit of UN Special Envoy Brahimi Detailed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Visit of UN Special Envoy Brahimi Detailed </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Briefs Saudi Officials </H4>

<F P=102> LD1106133794 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 1216 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1106133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Jeddah, 11 Jun -- Yemeni sources here expected 
the arrival of the southern Yemeni official, Abu Bakr al-'Attas, 
to Jeddah to meet the UN envoy to Yemen, Lakhdar Brahimi, who 
arrived in Saudi Arabia late last night from Amman with a 
mission aimed at ending the current crisis in Yemen. 
  Diplomatic sources told KUNA that Brahimi would hold talks 
with Saudi officials here to acquaint them with the latest 
developments in Yemen, particularly after 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih's 
welcome of a Saudi role to settle the Yemeni crisis completely. 
[passage omitted] 
  In contact with KUNA, Yemeni sources said that Haydar Abu 
Bakr al-'Attas, prime minister of the Democratic Republic of 
Yemen, which was recently proclaimed, and its foreign affairs 
minister, 'Abdallah al-Asnaj, would arrive in Jeddah at a later 
time to start talks with the UN envoy, which would be completed 
in Mukkala if a real cease-fire agreement was reached. 
  It is worth mentioning that Saudi Arabia has so far not 
officially announced that it was hosting these talks. However, 
according to Yemeni sources, it is not unlikely that Saudi 
Arabia "would host these talks if al-'Attar and al-Asnaj arrived 
in the presence of a Gulf desire for immediate cease-fire." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

