<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak Receives Saudi Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mubarak Receives Saudi Foreign Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1106121394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1045 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1106121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 11 Jun (MENA)--President Husni Mubarak has 
received a message from King Fahd Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz, monarch of 
Saudi Arabia and custodian of the two holy mosques. The 
message, dealing with bilateral ties and the continuing 
coordination between the two leaders over matters related to the 
current Arab situation, was delivered by Saudi Foreign Minister 
Prince Sa'ud al-Faysal, who arrived in Cairo earlier today. 
  After the meeting, Prince Sa'ud al-Faysal said that Egypt 
and 
Saudi Arabia are very concerned about stopping the fighting in 
Yemen. He said events in that country are very critical, 
declaring: We are devoting our efforts and energies to ensure a 
successful cease-fire for the good of all parties. 
  Regarding north Yemen's noncompliance with the UN Security 
Council resolution to observe a cease-fire, al-Faysal said that 
continued fighting hinders everything and does not merely hurt 
Yemen but its neighboring Arab countries as well. 
  Remarking that the wish to end the fighting in Yemen is 
shared by all the Arab countries, he voiced hope that this wish 
will find a favorable response, particularly during the current 
mission of the UN secretary general's envoy there. 
  Asked about the Gulf Cooperation Council's [GCC] position on 
the Yemeni crisis, the Saudi Foreign minister referred to the 
GCC statement on the issue and explained that its stance is 
clear. The GCC believes that continued fighting will force the 
GCC countries to adopt measures against the party that refuses 
the cease-fire. He said: Let us give the UN envoy a chance to 
make some efforts in this matter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

