<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kashmir `Militants' Fire Rocket at Radio Transmitter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kashmir `Militants' Fire Rocket at Radio Transmitter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1106091094 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1106091094 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In the Kashmir Valley, militants fired a rocket and 
resorted to heavy firing last night on a building in Srinagar 
which houses the transmitter of the commercial service of Radio 
Kashmir. It however did not cause any damage to the transmitter. 
The militants fled when security fores returned the fire. 
Meanwhile, three militants and two jawans [soldiers] of 
paramilitary forces were killed and 11 others injured in 
separate incidents during the past 24 hours. The security 
forces have sealed off the Batamaloo area in central Srinagar to 
flush out militants. 
  Authorities in Srinagar are hopeful of securing an early 
release of the two British trekkers who were kidnapped by 
militants five days ago. An official spokesman said the safety 
of the kidnapped persons is the first priority of the 
authorities. The father of one of the kidnapped persons told 
AIR [All India Radio] Srinagar correspondent that efforts are 
under way for an early release of the hostages. He also 
appreciated the role of the authorities in this connection. 

</TEXT>

