<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visit of Bosnian Foreign Minister Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Visit of Bosnian Foreign Minister Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Ljubijankic Arrives; Meets Velayati </H4>

<F P=102> LD1006103494 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0930 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1006103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Irfan Ljubijankic, Minister of Foreign Affairs of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, arrived in Tehran this morning at the head 
of a delegation and was welcomed by Foreign Affairs Minister 
Velayati. 
  During the Bosnian-Herzegovinan foreign minister's visit to 
Tehran, apart from talks on bilateral relations and the latest 
developments in that country, the agreements reached between the 
two countries during the visit to Tehran by the prime minister 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina will also be discussed. 
  On arrival in Tehran, the Bosnian-Herzegovinan foreign 
minister said: We are seeking appropriate grounds to establish 
peace, but as the main causes of the war in Bosnia are still 
there, the achievement of peace seems difficult. 
  On the Bosnian Government's views on the UN Security 
Council's disagreement with the dispatch of peace-keeping forces 
from Islamic countries to Bosnia he said: The Government of 
Bosnia continues its efforts to win the agreement of that 
organization [UN] for the dispatch of forces from Islamic 
countries, particularly from the Islamic Republic of Iran. 
  The Bosnian foreign minister said that among the reasons for 
the Western countries' contradictory handling of the Bosnian 
problem are their national interests and strategic 
considerations. 

</TEXT>

