<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Sends Rabin Letters on Aid, Jerusalem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Sends Rabin Letters on Aid, Jerusalem </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Rabin Reponds to 'Arafat's Aid Requests </H4>

<F P=102> TA1406083794 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 14 Jun 94 
pp 1, 19 </F>

<F P=103> TA1406083794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Shim'on Schiffer] </F>
  [Excerpts] PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat has asked Prime 
Minister Yitzhaq Rabin to grant financial aid to the Palestinian 
autonomy in the Gaza Strip and Jericho, which is in dire 
economic straits. 
  This request is included in one of 'Arafat's three letters 
to 
Rabin. 
  Officials in the prime minister's bureau have said that in 
consultations held on the formulation of a reply to 'Arafat's 
missives, Rabin ruled that Israel cannot help the PLO, either 
directly or indirectly. 
  A senior political source said yesterday that at a time when 
Israel lacks the necessary funds to help the Histadrut labor 
federation's sick fund, it cannot show generosity toward the 
PLO. At the same time, Rabin intends to formulate his reply in a 
positive spirit. [passage omitted] 
  In the letters 'Arafat sent to Rabin, the PLO chairman 
proposes, among other things, to begin discussions as soon as 
possible on the early empowerment of the autonomy institutions 
throughout the rest of the West Bank. Rabin intends to accede 
to this request, and contacts will soon be held between PLO 
officials and Israeli political figures in a bid to organize 
talks on this issue. 
  As reported yesterday in YEDI'OT AHARONOT, 'Arafat proposed 
that he and Rabin speak directly to one another and stressed the 
importance of establishing a "hot line" between them. 
  'Arafat also demanded that Rabin reaffirm Israel's 
commitment 
to preserve the status of Palestinian institutions in East 
Jerusalem. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

