<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy Brahimi Arrives in Amman En Route to Jeddah </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Envoy Brahimi Arrives in Amman En Route to Jeddah </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1006155294 Amman Jordan Television Network in Arabic 1500 
GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1006155294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Lakhdar Brahimi, the UN secretary 
general's envoy to Yemen, has arrived in Amman on his way to 
Jeddah. 
  He was received by Talal Sat'an al-Hasan, minister of state 
for foreign affairs; 'Ali Abu-Luhum, the Yemeni ambassador in 
Amman; the UN representative in Jordan; and the Saudi charge 
d'affaires in Amman. 
  Lakhdar Brahimi spoke to our political affairs 
correspondent: 
  [Begin recording] [Correspondent] Are you carrying specific 
ideas from the UN secretary general to the officials of both 
sides [of Yemen]? 
  [Brahimi] The ideas are very simple. War and internecine 
fighting will not solve the problem, dialogue is the preferable 
means, and the international community is ready to help if 
possible. However, these brothers can solve their problem among 
themselves. 
  [Correspondent] What do you expect the alternatives will be? 
  [Brahimi] It is premature to discuss options. At present, 
the urgent objective is to have a serious cease-fire, to respect 
the cease-fire, and to resume the dialogue. The brothers in 
Sanaa say that they accept the principle of dialogue, even 
though they say that this dialogue should be based on 
principles. They have their own principles. We told them that 
is alright, and undoubtedly the brothers in the other party have 
their own ideas and principles. If the principles are accepted, 
then we will examine the bases, conditions, and circumstances 
under which this dialogue will take place. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

