<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Muntasir Addresses OAU Meeting on Lockerbie Suspects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Muntasir Addresses OAU Meeting on Lockerbie Suspects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006193794 Tripoli JANA in Arabic 1610 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006193794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli JANA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Tripoli, 10 Jun -- Brother 'Umar al-Muntasir, 
secretary of the General People's Committee for Foreign Liaison 
and International Cooperation, delivered a speech [words 
indistinct]. 
  He added [words indistinct] that what has become known as 
the 
"Lockerbie" crisis, which was made public in a sudden and 
planned manner on 1 November 1991, and despite the numerous 
efforts and initiatives...[agency ellipses] the three Western 
countries insisted on transforming a legal conflict into a 
political issue to achieve [word indistinct] against the Great 
Jamahiriyah, and resorted to the UN Security Council and issued 
three resolutions, 731/92, 748/92, and 883/93. Despite that, 
the Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriyah agreed to deal 
with Resolution No. 731/92 and took practical measures to 
respond to [word indistinct] condemning terrorism in all its 
forms...[agency ellipses] complete readiness to cooperate with 
any quarter combating terrorism, affirmed that there were no 
camps for training terrorists, and repeated its call for the UN 
secretary general to send a fact-finding mission to investigate 
that. 
  He added: "The only remaining part to complete the 
implementation of UN Security Council Resolution No. 731 was 
that the two suspects appear before justice. As it is the case 
in all countries of the world, laws stipulated that the 
nationals of a given country should not be handed over for trial 
in other countries. Nevertheless, the Basic People's Congresses 
issued a decision stating that they did not object to the two 
suspects appearing before a fair and transparent court to be 
agreed upon." [passage omitted] 
  He stressed: "The Great Jamahiriyah insisted that the venue 
for the court must have all objective conditions required in any 
just court, because what was reported by Western media, what was 
written by a former CIA agent in his book, and what was 
announced by the director of the Swedish electronics firm that 
manufactured the timing devices refuted the main point in the 
charges against the two Libyan nationals, against whom the 
Western media had issued a verdict condemning them in advance. 
We would like to say here that this conference, in its 59th 
session, had called for a fair trial in a neutral venue. 
  He said for the sake of showing justice, the Socialist 
People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriyah did not object to the suspects 
appearing in front of a just and honest court that had all the 
psychological and legal requirements in order to achieve the 
truth, and to do the victims and their families justice. 
  He added: "You might agree with me that the style of the 
three countries [words indistinct] in tackling the case has 
caused us clear damage and injustice, and is not helping to 
solve the crisis in a satisfactory way." 
  He said: "In this context we would like to point out that 
international legal experts have studied the idea of trying the 
suspects at the headquarters of the International Court of 
Justice. [Word indistinct] and that the suspects' lawyer has 
agreed [word indistinct] to end the efforts to impose additional 
sanctions that will increase the suffering of the Libyan Arab 
people who have endured great losses as a result of the unjust 
sanctions of the UN Security Council Resolutions 748 and 883." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

