<H3> <TI>   Shabwah Governor Cites Success Against North </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shabwah Governor Cites Success Against North </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1306152194 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 13 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM1306152194 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Abdallah Hammudah: "In Exclusive Statement to </F>
AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT Shabwah Governor Says: I Invite Lakhdar 
Brahimi To Ascertain Our Victories. I Am Finding Difficulty in 
Compelling Tribes To Stop Fighting"] 
  [Excerpts] London -- Shabwah Governor Ahmad Farid 
al-Suraymah has said: "I am complying with the cease-fire and 
Security Council Resolution 924 in my capacity as governor and 
military governor of Shabwah Governorate. However, I am finding 
difficulty in controlling the Shabwah tribes and compelling them 
to comply with this resolution since they have begun to pursue 
the northerners." 
  He said this over the telephone from his command post in 
'Armah (one of the directorates in Shabwah Governorate). The 
governor promised to exert his efforts to achieve discipline 
among the tribes. But he said: "It is a difficult task. It is 
a popular resistance, and I advise Brother President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih to withdraw the remnants of his forces from 
Shabwah, otherwise I will not be responsible." 
  The Shabwah governor stressed that he is now at the 
approaches of 'Ataq, capital of the governorate. And that the 
distance between him and it does not exceed 20 km. He added 
that his forces have recaptured most of the governorate's 
territory, except some five square km in the city of 'Ataq 
itself. And that he has achieved total control for the southern 
authorities over the cities of Nisab, al-Musayni'ah, and 'Armah. 
[passage omitted] 
  The Shabwah governor said that he had invited Lakhdar 
Brahimi, envoy of the UN secretary general, to visit the 
governorate "in order to ascertain that we are in control of 
more than 90 percent of its territory. We are awaiting him." 
He added that this "refutes (President) 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih's 
allegation that Shabwah is under his control." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

