<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sanaa Official on Brahimi's Talks in South </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sanaa Official on Brahimi's Talks in South </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1406064094 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 0500 GMT 14 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1406064094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] UN Envoy Lakhdar Brahimi has informed the Sanaa 
government of the southern leaders' conditions and demands for 
beginning negotiations on the Yemeni dispute. 
  A ranking northern Yemeni official told AFP that Lakhdar 
Brahimi contacted the leaders in Sanaa and communicated to them 
a list of questions and points pertaining to the guarantees the 
southerners want fulfilled to initiate negotiations with Sanaa. 
  The official added that the working group, chaired by 
President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih and tasked with holding contacts 
with Aden, will meet today to discuss these questions. The 
northern official did not elaborate further on these questions. 
However, Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas, the prime minister of the 
Democratic Republic of Yemen, unilaterally proclaimed by the 
southerners, said that Aden calls for an unconditional and 
immediate cease-fire, the deployment of international observers 
to supervise its implementation, and the return of the 
aggressors, as he called them, to the pre-22 May 1990 borders, 
the date unity was declared. 
  Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas said this following his meeting 
with UN Envoy Lakhdar Brahimi in al-Mukalla yesterday evening, 
who later met with southern leader 'Ali Salim al-Bid. Following 
the meeting, 'Ali Salim al-Bid said that he briefed Brahimi on 
the deteriorating situation in Yemen, reemphasizing that 
priority should be given to a cease-fire. 
  Lakhdar Brahimi, contrary to what the southern officials 
wanted, did not visit Aden. He said this is due to the security 
instability there. 
  Brahimi left al-Mukalla for Abu Dhabi where he arrived 
yesterday evening accompanied by Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas. The 
Emirates News Agency says that Brahimi's visit to Abu Dhabi is 
part of a tour of several Arab countries in the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

