<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   DRY Claims Need for International Observers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DRY Claims Need for International Observers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1406112494 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 14 Jun 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1406112494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Abdallah Hammudah and Lutfi Shatarah: </F>
"Questions in Yemeni Streets About Benefit of Continuing War"] 
  [Excerpts] London, Sanaa, Aden, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT, SPA -- 
International envoy Lakhdar Brahimi yesterday concluded his 
visit to Yemen and meetings with the parties to the war there 
without being able to visit Aden as a result of the northern 
bombardment of it. [passage omitted] 
  Brahimi ended his meetings with southern leaders with a 
lunch 
meeting yesterday in 'Ali Salim al-Bid's house. The meeting was 
attended by Engineer Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas, prime minister 
of the Democratic Republic of Yemen [DRY]; Foreign Minister 
'Abdallah al-Asnaj; and Muhsin Bin-Farid, deputy prime minister 
and planning minister. 
  Muhsin Bin-Farid told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT over the telephone 
from al-Mukalla yesterday that Brahimi met the day before 
yesterday with representatives of the political parties and 
organizations and ulemas. He also met with al-'Attas and 
al-Asnaj, stressing that "his basic mission is to listen to the 
southern leadership's view in the framework of the fact-finding 
process." He was provided with a detailed memorandum on the 
southern position. 
  Bin-Farid added that the southern leaders told Brahimi "of 
the need to impose the will of international legitimacy on the 
party violating the cease-fire" in accordance with Security 
Council Resolution 924, which stipulates "an immediate halt to 
the fighting and sitting at the negotiating table." 
  Bin-Farid said that the continuation of the fighting in 
Yemen 
-- despite Brahimi's visit -- "represents an attempt by Sanaa to 
use the fighting as a means to seize more land in southern 
governorates, while continuing to announce cease-fire 
initiatives merely to deceive foreign public opinion and impose 
a fait accompli." He also called for "adopting more powerful 
resolutions to force it to halt the fighting." 
  The southern official said that DRY leaders raised during 
their meetings with Brahimi the need to dispatch international 
observers "to supervise and consolidate the cease-fire." He 
said that "there have to be a third party in order to ascertain 
the quarter violating the resolution." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

