<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hamas Renews Call for Prisoner Release </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hamas Renews Call for Prisoner Release </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1306191494 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1306191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Shlomi Eldar] </F>
  [Excerpts] The issue of the Palestinian prisoners is 
turning into the central issue in the territories in 
anticipation of Yasir 'Arafat's arrival. Hamas [Islamic 
Resistance Movement] and the rejectionist organizations are 
calling for mass demonstrations in the Gaza Strip to protest the 
delay in the release of the prisoners. A leaflet distributed 
today says that the terrorist Rabin -- as the leaflet depicts 
him -- cannot be expected to release the prisoners. Almost 300 
prisoners who according to the Oslo agreement must remain in the 
autonomous area are grounded in Jericho at the present time. Our 
correspondent Shlomi Eldar reports: 
  [Begin Eldar recording] The pressure being exerted by the 
families of the Palestinians behind bars imprisoned in Israeli 
prisons is growing. In a mass demonstration organized by George 
Habash's Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, Habash's 
picture was hoisted alongside that of thousands of prisoners. 
So far Israel has released less than one half of the security 
prisoners it promised to release, and this issue tops all other 
issues on Gaza's public agenda. This pressure has reached 
'Arafat. He knows that without affecting the release of the 
prisoners he will not be able to come to Gaza and Jericho with 
peace of mind. Today he sent Brigadier Ziyad al-Atrash to 
address the crowds on his behalf. [passage omitted] 
  Al-Atrash will in all likelihood convey a message to 'Arafat 
advising him not to arrive in Gaza and Jericho before he 
succeeds in dissolving this protest movement. 
  The thousands of demonstrators later held a protest march in 
Gaza City, chanting slogans calling for the release of the 
prisoners. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

