<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Sends Rabin Letters on Aid, Jerusalem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Sends Rabin Letters on Aid, Jerusalem </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Offers To Postpone Jerusalem Issue </H4>

<F P=102> NC1306094794 Paris AFP in English 0755 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1306094794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jerusalem, June 13 (AFP)--PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat 
has agreed to drop the stormy debate over Jerusalem "for the 
time being", a senior foreign ministry official said Monday. 
  'Arafat had made the offer in a series of letters sent to 
Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin last week after a major rumpus over 
the fate of the city both sides claim as capital. 
  "The PLO leader expressed his intention to smooth over 
differences and reduce tension," the official told AFP. "He is 
ready to withdraw the question of Jerusalem from the agenda for 
the time being." 
  Arafat also urged Israel to respect the written undertaken 
from Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres last October to allow 
Palestinian institutions to continue operating in East 
Jerusalem. [sentence as received] 
  Under the Declaration of Principles for autonomy, the 
Jerusalem issue would not be raised until the third year of 
Palestinian self-rule when negotiations on a permanent 
settlement are set to be begin. 
  Israel captured East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 war 
and has declared the united city its eternal capital. The PLO 
demands to share Jerusalem. 
  Meanwhile, the HA'ARETZ newspaper reported that the 
government had decided not to allow 'Arafat to enter East 
Jerusalem during his visit to the autonomous Palestinian areas 
which is expected to take place sometime this month. 
  The army had voiced that 'Arafat's arrival in East Jerusalem 
would lead to clashes between Palestinians and the Israeli 
right-wing. Some extremists have called for 'Arafat to be 
murdered. 
  Rabin said last month that the PLO leader would not be 
allowed into Jerusalem for at least two years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

