<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yemeni Justice Minister Arrives on Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yemeni Justice Minister Arrives on Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    To Convey Message From Salih </H4>

<F P=102> JN1006185694 Amman Jordan Television Network in Arabic 1700 
GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1006185694 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "60 Minutes" program] </F>
  [Text] [Announcer] 'Abdallah Ahmad Ghanim, Yemeni minister 
of justice and envoy of the Yemeni Government, arrived in Amman 
today from Damascus with a message for His Majesty King Husayn 
from His brother Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih. 
  The Yemeni envoy made a statement to our political affairs 
correspondent: 
  [Begin recording] [Ghanim] My current visit to the fraternal 
Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan is to convey a message from 
Presidential Council Chairman 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih to his 
brother His Majesty King Husayn dealing with the latest 
developments in the Republic of Yemen, with stopping this war 
which was ignited by the secessionist rebels, and with the full 
implementation of the UN Security Council resolution which 
safeguards Yemen's territorial integrity. 
  [Correspondent] Mr. Minister, is there Yemeni action on the 
Arab level? 
  [Ghanim] Yes, there is Yemeni action. My visit to Jordan is 
part of this action. It is the first leg of a tour of a number 
of fraternal Arab states in order to brief them on the true 
situation in Yemen. 
  [Correspondent] What is the true situation in Yemen 
regarding 
the cease-fire? 
  [Ghanim] The true situation in Yemen is the tragedy that has 
been caused by some of the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] leaders 
through their rebellion and insurgence against the authority and 
public order. They did this to pave the way for announcing 
secession in order to take Yemen back to the pre-22 May [1990] 
era in violation of the Yemeni people's will, the constitution, 
and the April 1993 elections, which the whole world admitted 
were clean elections. Regarding the cease-fire, the Republic of 
Yemen has from the very beginning welcomed the UN Security 
Council resolution calling for an immediate cease-fire although 
we are convinced that this resolution is interference in our 
internal affairs. Despite this, out of our respect for 
international legitimacy, we welcomed this resolution and 
complied with it. As of yesterday, the legitimate leadership in 
the Republic of Yemen had announced a cease-fire three times. 
Regrettably, every time, the rebels violate this cease-fire, 
foment sedition, and renew fighting. There objective is to 
continue the battles to create an appropriate atmosphere to 
bring forces to disengage both Yemeni sides' troops, or 
international observers. We consider this a flagrant 
interference in the internal Yemeni affairs. 
  [Correspondent] In a statement, the UN envoy said that 
officials in Sanaa accept dialogue, and the other party might 
accept dialogue. Do you consider this a turning point in the 
situation in general? 
  [Ghanim] We have accepted dialogue from the beginning. We 
have never refused to extend our hand for the sake of dialogue 
and national reconciliation. After the declaration of 
secession, dialogue has become possible only with the YSP 
leaders who believe in unity and democracy. However, it is 
difficult to hold dialogue with the members who do not believe 
in unity, declared secession, and disavowed democracy. 
  [Correspondent] Thank you Mr. Minister. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

