<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy Denies Test-Firing of DPRK Missile </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Envoy Denies Test-Firing of DPRK Missile </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306145194 Tehran IRNA in English 1343 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1306145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] June 13, IRNA -- Iran's ambassador to Tokyo, Hoseyn 
Kazempur-Ardebili here today denied a KYODO report that Iran was 
test-firing N. Korean missile. 
  KYODO on Sunday quoted a U.S. weekly, "U.S. NEWS AND WORLD 
REPORT," that Japan was urging Iran to stop the missile test. 
  In a letter to managing director of the International 
Department of KYODO news service, the ambassador said the United 
States has launched a campaign to pressure Japan and other 
industrial countries to limit their commercial activities with 
Iran by raising such allegations. 
  "Regarding our nuclear program, as part of its post-war 
reconstruction, Iran has sought to repair its damaged industrial 
infrastructure. Major damage was inflicted on Iran's power 
generation facilities. To deal with this urgent problem and to 
meet the growing demand of the population, Iran has looked to 
other sources. Major investments have been made in the past 20 
years in nuclear power generation and it is natural to continue 
and build on these investments for the immediate and prospective 
power needs of the nation," the ambassador said. 
  "Our nuclear facilities have been visited and inspected by 
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and their peaceful 
applications have been verified," said the ambassador. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

