<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iran's Velayati Meets Musa, Denies Aiding Terrorists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iran's Velayati Meets Musa, Denies Aiding Terrorists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1506064394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2110 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1506064394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 14 Jun (MENA)--Iranian Foreign Minister 'Ali 
Akbar Velayati has said that his various meetings with Egyptian 
Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa dealt, in total frankness, with the 
views of Iran and Egypt on many current issues and with ways to 
build confidence between the two countries. 
  In a statement to AL-AHRAM, which the paper will publish 
tomorrow, Wednesday, Velayati denied that his country has 
assisted any terrorist group in Egypt or Algeria. He also 
denied that Iran is holding Egyptian prisoners since the 
Iraq-Iran war. All Egyptian prisoners were handed over to 
Egypt, he said. 
  Velayati invited the foreign minister of the United Arab 
Emirates [UAE] to visit Tehran to continue the peaceful dialogue 
on the future of the three UAE islands. This dialogue stopped 
about a year ago. 
  Velayati said: If there is a solution to this problem, then 
it must be found through peaceful dialogue. But if one side 
tries to get others involved in the situation or 
internationalize the issue, then this side will lose more. 
  The Iranian foreign minister expressed his belief that the 
security of the Gulf region starts with economic, political, and 
security cooperation, but he admitted that the essence of this 
idea has not been discussed. 
  Velayati said that Iran's spending on armaments, considering 
the population, is less than that of any country in the region. 
He said Iran spends only 4 percent of its budget on arms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

