<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Bid, UN's Brahimi Discuss Crisis, Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Bid, UN's Brahimi Discuss Crisis, Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA1406192694 Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in Arabic 1500 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1406192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in Arabic 1500 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brother 'Ali Salim al-Bid, the chairman of the 
Presidential Council, received in al-Mukalla yesterday Mr. 
Lakhdar Brahimi, the envoy of the UN secretary general, with 
whom he discussed developments affecting the situation in the 
Yemeni arena and the UN envoy's efforts to bring about the 
implementation of UN Security Council Resolution No. 924 calling 
for an immediate cease-fire and talks between the conflicting 
sides. 
  Brother al-Bid very warmly welcomed Mr. Brahimi to our 
country and expressed appreciation for the role he was 
performing toward rescuing Yemen from the calamity now 
afflicting its people. The brother chairman of the Presidential 
Council reiterated Democratic Yemen's position from which it was 
calling for an immediate cease-fire and implementation of the UN 
Security Council's resolution for the sake of the national 
interest and in response to the international will. He stressed 
that our country and people had rejected the principle of 
solving differences by resorting to arms. He briefed the UN 
envoy on the efforts made and continuing to be made by our 
political leadership to shield the Yemeni people from the 
suffering inflicted on them daily as the result of this war 
which 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih and the al-Ahmar gang had imposed on 
our people. 
  For his part, Lakhdar Brahimi reiterated the hope that the 
conflicting parties would observe the cease-fire resolution. He 
also briefed the brother chairman of the Presidential Council on 
the results of his meetings with the Sanaa leadership. The 
meeting was attended by brothers Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas, the 
prime minister; Muhsin Muhammad Abu-Bakr Bin-Farid, deputy prime 
minister and minister of planning and development; and 'Abdallah 
al-Asnaj, deputy prime minister and foreign minister. 

</TEXT>

