<H3> <TI>   Sanaa Said To Reject Aden's Proposals to UN </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sanaa Said To Reject Aden's Proposals to UN </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WA1506015394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2235 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WA1506015394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, 14 Jun (MENA)--A responsible source in north 
Yemen has stressed that the Yemeni Government rejected the 
proposals that the rebels made today to Lakhdar Brahimi, UN 
envoy to Yemen. 
  In a statement broadcast here tonight, the source fully 
denied news media reports that Yemen had accepted the proposals. 
In spirit and essence, the source said, the proposals 
constitute a flagrant violation of Security Council Resolution 
No. 924, and they contradict the resolution in text and spirit, 
as the source put it. 
  The source said Yemen had announced it had accepted 
discussion on the possibility of activating a joint military 
committee, which was formed by a decision from President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih, in its full formation. The committee comprises 
six Yemeni Armed Forces officers, five Jordanian officers, five 
Omani officers, and the military attaches of France and the 
United States in Yemen. 
  It should be noted that Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas, head of 
the proclaimed government in Aden, presented a proposal to 
Lakhdar Brahimi earlier today calling for the establishment of a 
team of observers drawn from a supervisory committee consisting 
of 11 military officers representing the Arab League, south 
Yemen, north Yemen, Oman, Jordan, and the military attaches of 
the United States, Russia, France, China, Britain, and a UN 
representative. 

</TEXT>

