<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   President, Kenya's Attorney General Discuss Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President, Kenya's Attorney General Discuss Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506111194 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0930 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506111194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Hashemi-Rafsanjani received Kenyan 
Attorney General Amos Wako this morning. After giving Mr. 
Hashemi-Rafsanjani a written message from the Kenyan president, 
the Kenyan attorney general described the outcome of his 
meetings with our country's judicial officials as very fruitful. 
  Thanking Iran for its efforts in the fight against narcotics 
and for observing human rights standards, he called for more 
cooperation and consultation regarding the sharing of Iran's 
invaluable experience with his country. 
  Thanking Iran for its foreign policy on establishing and 
expanding ties with the Third World, especially African 
countries, he described as very important and effective the role 
of our country's officials in global developments. He said: 
Since the victory of the Islamic revolution, as a big regional 
and Islamic power, Iran has played an active role in defending 
the rights of the innocent and the deprived throughout the 
world. He called for the expansion of mutual ties in all fields. 
  According to a Central News Unit report, President 
Hashemi-Rafsanjani expressed regret that monopolistic countries 
pursue their hegemonistic policy in the world by resorting to 
holy concepts. He said: The cruelty and harshness of those 
powers are known throughout history, and there is strong 
evidence of their disregard for human rights. They try to 
accuse developing countries and countries seeking independence 
of human rights violations. 
  He said: Using their capabilities, since they possess rich 
natural and human resources, Third World countries could, 
through cooperation--directly and without middlemen--help each 
other in solving their problems. 
  Expressing concern about the bitter events in Africa, 
particularly the events in Somalia, Rwanda, Angola, and 
Mozambique, the president called for more effort by the 
Organization of African Unity to end the crisis in that region. 
  He expressed the hope that relations between Iran and Kenya 
would be expanded in all fields. 

</TEXT>

