<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   * SALAM's Editor in Chief Freed After Making Payment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    * SALAM's Editor in Chief Freed After Making Payment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94LA0175B Tehran KEYHAN-E HAVA'I in Persian 27 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> 94LA0175B </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran KEYHAN-E HAVA'I </F>
<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] Tehran, 3 Farvardin [19 April] KEYHAN News Service 
-- 'Abbas 'Abdi, editor in chief of the newspaper SALAM, who was 
arrested early in the month of Shahrivar [23 August-22 September 
1993] and was sentenced on 1 Dey [22 December] at the 
revolutionary court to one year in prison and 40 lashes in 
suspension, was released on a bond payment of 10 million tumans. 
  The newspaper SALAM made the point that 'Abdi has served 10 
months of his sentence and only four months remain, and that 
taking a 10-million-tuman bond to free him is not appropriate 
for the remaining time. It regarded this as a violation of 
judicial procedure. 
  During the month of Dey [22 December 1993-20 January 1994], 
concurrent with the issuance of the sentence punishing 'Abdi and 
the press discussions concerning the nature of his crime, the 
deputy minister of guidance for press affairs said: The charges 
against 'Abbas 'Abdi are not press related. 

</TEXT>

