<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Majali Leaves to Join King in U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Majali Leaves to Join King in U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1406161494 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1500 GMT 
14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1406161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali left 
Amman [for Washington] this afternoon to join his Majesty King 
Husayn. 
  In a press statement at Queen Alia Airport prior to his 
departure, Dr. al-Majali said that the summit due to be held 
between His Majesty King Husayn and U.S. President Bill Clinton 
is important. He added that during this summit, the two leaders 
will discuss the means of promoting and enhancing Jordanian-U.S. 
ties, regional developments, and international issues. Dr. 
al-Majali went on to say: They will also discuss the most 
recent developments in the peace process, particularly those 
relating to the Jordanian track of negotiations, as well as the 
negotiations on the other tracks, especially the Syrian and 
Lebanese tracks of negotiations, because we believe that the 
negotiations on these tracks should see progress. Jordan's firm 
position underscores the need for a comprehensive solution. He 
noted that the progress made on one track is also good for the 
other tracks of negotiations. 
  On inter-Arab coordination at this phase, the prime minister 
said: The concept of coordination is not being seriously 
observed. The level of inter-Arab coordination has not risen to 
the desired levels. He indicated that coordination among the 
Arab sides engaged in the peace process has continued to take 
place whenever there is an opportunity to do so. He added that 
whenever new developments occur, the other parties are informed 
of this. He noted that this is done constantly. 
  With regard to the issue of al-'Aqabah, Dr. al-Majali said 
that the Jordanian Government is about to sign a deal in this 
regard with Lloyds Register. He noted that there is a minor 
problem hampering this, and that this minor problem is about to 
be resolved. 
  The prime minister was seen off at the airport by Deputy 
Prime Minister Dhuqan al-Hindawi, several cabinet ministers, the 
chief of Public Security, and several other officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

