<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Source': Amman's Stance `Identical' to Syria's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Source': Amman's Stance `Identical' to Syria's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1506075894 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 14 Jun 94 p1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1506075894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Salamah Ni'mat: "Jordan Considers Its Position </F>
`Identical' to the Syrian Position"] 
  [Text] Amman -- A reliable Jordanian source said yesterday 
that the forthcoming Jordanian-Israeli negotiations on Israeli 
withdrawal from the occupied Jordanian territory before entering 
into "normalization agreements" are identical with the Syrian 
position which calls on Israel "to withdraw fully in return for 
full peace." 
  The source told AL-HAYAH that Jordan's demands for the 
return 
of its occupied territory and for the definition and demarcation 
of its international borders are "equal to the Sryian call for 
Israeli withdrawal from the occupied Golan in return for peace 
with Israel." The source noted that Damascus "called for 
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan in return for peace, not 
withdrawal from all the occupied Arab territories including the 
Jordanian, Palestinian, and Lebanese territories." He added 
that a definition and demarcation of the Jordanian borders 
"would help in the demarcation of the border of the future 
Palestinian state...east of the West Bank." 
  The informed source stressed that "when the question of the 
Palestinian Golan was mentioned, Jordan's aim in talking about 
it was to support the Syrian position that that territory is 
Syrian...certainly not Israeli." 
  Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali had said at a 
closed session of the House of Representatives last week that a 
dispute over the ownership of al-Himmah triangle known as the 
"Palestinian Golan" was one of the most important obstacles 
standing in the way of a draft agreement with Israel on the 
Syrian Golan Heights. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

