<F P=100> Western Sahara </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polisario Statement on Voters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Polisario Statement on Voters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1106135594 Algiers Radio Algiers Network in Arabic 1200 
GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1106135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Radio Algiers Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New developments have taken place in the Saharan 
voters' registration issue. After new information was given by 
the Saharan side with regard to the travel by thousands of 
Moroccan citizens to the Saharan territory, the UN mission in 
charge of organizing the referendum in Western Sahara denied 
this information. Over to you Abdelkader Cherti, 
  [Abdelkeder] In a statement delivered to APS yesterday, the 
Popular Front for the Liberation of Saquia El Hamra and Rio de 
Oro [Polisario] affirmed the arrival by bus in recent days of 
thousands of Moroccan citizens in Laayoune and Bojador to 
participate in the voter identification, which started in 
Western Sahara under UN supervision before the organization of 
the referendum on self-determination in Western Sahara. 
  The Polisario Front said that the operation is considered a 
blatant violation of the UN peace plan in Western Sahara and the 
aim behind it is to undermine the referendum and spoil the 
atmosphere in which the UN committee for voter identification 
works. 
  In view of these developments, the Polisario Front called on 
UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali and the UN Security 
Council to take the necessary measures to guarantee the smooth 
operation of voter identification in an atmosphere of freedom 
and strictness. 
  In contrast with the contents of the Polisario Front's 
statement, the UN committee in charge of implementing the 
referendum in Western Sahara denied yesterday evening the 
information contained in the Saharan statement and stressed that 
they did not notice buses loaded with Moroccan citizens, and, 
according to their statement, they did not receive any 
information to this effect. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-36960 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes115_i_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-115 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Western Sahara </F>
<H3> <TI>   MINURSO Refutes Polisario Claims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MINURSO Refutes Polisario Claims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1106113794 Rabat MAP in Arabic 1010 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1106113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rabat MAP </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rabat, 11 Jun -- "MINURSO," the UN mission in charge 
of organizing the referendum in the Sahara, refuted the news 
reported by the "Polisario" [Popular Front for the Liberation of 
Saquia El Hamra and Rio de Oro] from Algeria, which maintained 
that several thousand Moroccans have arrived in the Sahara. 
  A MINURSO official pointed out to AFP that "we have not 
noticed anything, and we have not seen any vehicles carrying 
persons to Laayoune, where the mission's headquarters are, and 
we have not received any information in this respect from other 
Saharan towns." 
  In a statement published in the capital Algiers, the 
"Polisario" had announced the arrival of several thousand 
Moroccans to the Sahara [word indistinct] in hundreds of buses. 

</TEXT>

